{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UNdJ2wyg2Fwt9uLmX8Med9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the issue. The `limit_req` is set with `burst=5 nodelay`. The burst size is 5, meaning the first 5 requests can all be served immediately even if they exceed the rate limit. The `nodelay` means they're served right away without delay.\n\nWith rate=1r/s, burst=5, nodelay:\n- The first 5 requests are served immediately (they fill the burst bucket)\n- After the burst is exhausted, only 1 req/s is allowed\n- But with 10 requests at 0.5s interval (5 seconds total), the burst absorbs all initial traffic\n- The bucket drains at 1r/s, so by the time request 6 arrives at t=2.5s, enough tokens have been replenished to serve it\n\nLet me recalculate the token bucket state more carefully as each request comes in. nodelay means the requests are served immediately rather than queued. With 10 requests arriving at 0.5-second intervals, the burst bucket allows up to 5 excess requests to be served right away before hitting the rate limit, and the debt clears at 1 request per second. Continuing through requests 4 through 8, the debt keeps accumulating but stays well below the burst limit of 5, so each request gets approved as it arrives.\n\nAt request 9, the debt hits exactly 5.0, which is still allowed since it equals the limit. But request 10 pushes it to 5.5, exceeding the threshold and getting rejected with a 429 response. This tells me the burst value of 5 is too permissive—I need to either lower the burst or find the right annotation in the nginx ingress controller to configure it properly. Let me reconsider how nginx actually tracks this. The algorithm maintains the time of the last allowed request, and for each new request, it calculates how much \"excess\" capacity has accumulated based on the time elapsed and the rate limit. If that excess exceeds the burst allowance, the request gets rejected; otherwise it's allowed. So with burst=0, the rate limiter enforces a strict 1 request per second, which means at 2 req/s roughly half the requests would get rejected with 429. I need to verify that ingress-nginx actually supports setting `limit-burst-multiplier` to 0, so let me check the documentation.\n\nThe docs confirm that `limit-burst-multiplier` overrides the default burst of 5, but setting it to 0 might not work as expected. I'll try setting it to 1 instead, which gives a burst of 1 extra request on top of the rate limit. With `limit-rps=1` and `burst-multiplier=1`, I should see roughly half of the 10 requests rejected when sending at 2 req/s. burst parameter in nginx controls how many excess requests can be queued beyond the steady rate, and with nodelay they're served immediately rather than delayed. For the ingress-nginx annotation, the burst size is calculated as rate multiplied by the limit-burst-multiplier, so with rate=1r/s and multiplier=1, I get a burst of 1 token that allows one extra request before hitting the limit.\n\nNow I'm realizing I need to trace through the actual nginx rate limiting algorithm more carefully—it tracks the last excess value and computes whether each new request exceeds the burst threshold based on how much time has passed since the last request and the configured rate. No. allowed.\n  - If burst=1: 1.5 > 1? Yes. REJECTED.\n  - If burst=0: 1.5 > 0? Yes. REJECTED.\n\nreq3 (t=1.0): elapsed=0.5, prev_excess=1.5 (if burst=5) or starts fresh from allowed (if burst=1, req2 rejected)\n\nHmm, this is getting complex. With burst=1:\n- req1: excess=1 ≤ 1, allowed. last_excess=1.\n- req2 (t=0.5): excess=max(0,1-0.5+1)=1.5 > 1. REJECTED.\n- req3 (t=1.0): excess=max(0,1-1.0+1)=1.0 ≤ 1. Allowed. last_excess=1.\n- req4 (t=1\n\n.5): excess=max(0,1-0.5+1)=1.5 > 1. REJECTED.\n- req5 (t=2.0): excess=max(0,1-1.0+1)=1.0 ≤ 1. Allowed. last_excess=1.\n\nSo the pattern alternates—every other request passes while the rest get rejected, giving us 5 allowed and 5 rejected requests, which meets the ≥4 429s requirement.\n\nBut I need to reconsider what happens when a request is rejected. The nginx module doesn't update last_excess on rejection, so it stays frozen at its previous value. This means req2's rejection doesn't change the state, and req3 calculates excess based on the unchanged last_excess from req1.\n\nWith `limit-rps: 1` and `limit-burst-multiplier: 1`, this alternating pattern should produce roughly 5 429 responses.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":649,"cache_read_input_tokens":48906,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":649},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bffc0ae9-9ad7-4bdb-ad72-c1a81edddf53","uuid":"edde66fb-735f-4d80-ae2a-eb1874b61b4a","request_id":"req_011Cc5AygugWnJUf99vRfrKd"}
